  _eventName: 'Google invests in mobility: a commitment to the future, but at what
    price?'
  _date: September 24, 2024
  _subheading: ' For several years now, Google has been positioning itself as a major
    player in the field of mobility. Indeed, the tech giant recently announced a
    strategic investment in mobility projects based on new technologies. The aim:
    to subsidize innovative initiatives capable of transforming the way we get around.
    But behind this stated desire to improve urban mobility, there''s a nagging question:
    what''s Google''s real interest in this approach?'
  _coverImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 63e7cdb0f96db1612b9b3ce7e5ed8081, type: 3}
  _captionImage: Aenean malesuada gravida diam, non tempus eros elementum vel. Phasellus
    pulvinar non nisl in sceler.
  _description: 'Ambitious projects to rethink transportation: Google, through its
    subsidiary Sidewalk Labs and partnerships with specialized companies, seeks to
    encourage more ecological and intelligent solutions, such as autonomous vehicles,
    shared mobility and intelligent public transportation systems. As part of this
    program, the American giant offers subsidies to startups and research projects
    that push the boundaries of technology to offer sustainable alternatives to the
    individual car. Google''s stated ambition is to reduce congestion in cities,
    promote energy efficiency, and enable smoother and less polluting travel. The
    company sees these mobility technologies as a way to optimize urban infrastructure
    while contributing to the fight against global warming. An investment tinged
    with commercial intentions: However, far from being satisfied with a simple philanthropic
    desire, Google is closely monitoring the development of these projects. While
    the promise of transforming mobility is appealing, some observers point out that
    these investments are also a way for Google to strengthen its dominant position
    in urban data. Collecting information on transport flows, travel habits, and
    the infrastructure of each city gives Google unprecedented power over citizens''
    daily habits. The giant could thus enrich its mapping and geolocation services,
    while consolidating its ecosystem of applications, such as Google Maps or Waze,
    which would increasingly be at the heart of smart mobility. In addition, through
    its initiatives, Google is ensuring that it plays a central role in the development
    of tomorrow''s technological infrastructures, or even to be directly involved
    in the implementation of these new transport solutions. While the project seems
    in line with a sustainable vision of the future, it nonetheless perfectly aligns
    Google''s commercial interests. Towards a future where mobility and technology
    merge? There is no reason to believe that these investments in mobility will
    be limited to one-off subsidies. In reality, Google seems well and truly determined
    to take a leading role in the reconfiguration of urban transport modes. But while
    we celebrate this evolution towards smarter and more interconnected cities, it
    is worth asking ourselves to what extent we will be ready to accept such a degree
    of technological control over our daily lives. While we can welcome the innovation
    and potential offered by these new technologies, it is important to remain vigilant
    about possible abuses. Google''s commitment to mobility could well redefine our
    travels... but also our relationship with data, surveillance, and automation.
    It remains to be seen whether this investment in mobility, presented as a step
    towards the future, will primarily serve the public interest, or whether the
    hidden intention is to make mobility a new source of profits for Google. //Effect:
    lower cost of "technological" projects'
